<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Mesh_function_arm  Entity: Mesh_function_basis  
   <express_ref linkend="mesh_function:arm:Mesh_function_arm.Mesh_function_basis"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Mesh_function_arm.Mesh_function_basis">
<p>
	A <b>Mesh_function_basis</b> is an application defined function that has:
</p>
	<ul>
		<li>a domain that is a real tuple space; and</li>
		<li>a range that is a space of table functions.</li>
	</ul>

	<note number="1">
		A <b>Mesh_function_basis</b> is used such that the domain is a parametric space that identifies points within a cell of a mesh. 
		Hence the dimension of the real tuple space is the same as the topological dimension of the cell.
	</note>
<p>
	Each table function in the range of a <b>Mesh_function_basis</b> has:
</p>
	<ul>
		<li>a domain that is a subscript space; and</li>
		<li>a range that is the reals.</li>
	</ul>

	<note number="2">
	<p>A <b>Mesh_function_basis</b> is used such that:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>the domain of each table function in its range is a parametric space that identifies the control values for a cell;</li>
			<li>the range of each table function is a weighting for a control value.</li>
		</ul>
	</note> 

<p>
	Each table function specifies the weightings for control values that define the value of a mesh function at a point in a cell.
</p>
	<note number="3"> 
		An Application Module can define a subtype of <b>Mesh_function_basis</b> and externally - defined item to record a standard instance 
		of a function such as the 'serendipity' function commonly used in finite element analysis.
	</note>
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Mesh_function_arm  Entity: Mesh_function_basis  Attribute: cell_topological_dimension 
